Prosper Loan data exploration¶

Preliminary wrangling¶

The prosper loan dataset is a financial dataset. Prosper is an American company that offers loans at low interest rates to the borrowers. The dataset is comprised of 81 variables and contains 113937 entries.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset has 113,937 entries with 81 columns.

What are the main features of interest in your dataset?¶

In the dataset, I will be investigating what influences loan performance in association with borrowers and lenders.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigstion into your feature(s) of interest?¶
  1. Term - The length of the loan expressed in months
  2. BorrowerRate - The Borrower's interest rate for this loan
  3. ProsperRating (Alpha) - The prosper rating assigned at the time the listing was created between AA-HR. Applicable for loas originated after July 2009
  4. StatedMonthlyIncome - The monthly income the borrower stated at the time the listing was created
  5. EmploymentStatus - The employmentstatus of the borrower at the time the listing is created.
  6. EstimatedReturn - The estimated return assigned to the listing at the time it was created.
  7. LoanOriginalAmount - The origination amount of the loan

Prosper changed Credit Grade to Prosper Rating after 2009, that is why Prosper Rating is missing some values. We will merge credit grade with prosper rating.

In [ ]:
#merge NC and HR
df['CreditGrade'].replace(['NC', 'HR'], 'E', inplace=True)

#handle null values
df['CreditGrade'].fillna("", inplace=True)
df['ProsperRating (Alpha)'].fillna("", inplace=True)

#merge credit ratings
df['ProsperRatingMerged'] = df['ProsperRating (Alpha)'] + df['CreditGrade']

#drop rows
df = df.query('ProsperRatingMerged != ""')

#value count

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The variables of interest in this investigation were: Term, BorrowerRate, ProsperRating, StatedMonthlyIncome, ListingCategory, EstimatedReturn, LoanOriginalAmount.

Normal distributions for term, BorrowerRate, ProsperRating, StatedMonthlyIncome, ListingCategory, EstimatedReturn, LoanOriginalAmount were observed.

StatedMonthlyIncome had many entries with the value of 0, this seems to to show that most people don't have a monthly income. There were bo transformations done on the features stated above

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

To tidy the data, I removed null values from EstimatedReturn. I did this in order to have better data when plotting histograms in order to have correct values. I adjusted and changed the ProsperRating by merging with CreditGrade, this enabled to cover all entries pre-2009 and post-2009.

From the boxplots, we can see that the people who are self-employed have a the highest range of estimated return, while people who are retired have the lowest estimated return.

The estimated return increase with a better prosper rating.

We can speculate that people who are self-employed have higher cash flows to repay their loans while people who are retired have stopped working and don't have consistent incomes.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the datasrt? Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

From the matrix plot we observe that term had no correlation with the other features. There is a correlation between Borrower rate and Estimated Return, a correlation between Borrower rate and Stated Monthly Income, no correlation between StatedMonthlyIncome ad Estimated Return, is no correlation between StatedMonthlyIncome and BorrowerRate, a correlation between EstimatedReturn and StatedMonthlyIncome and a correlation between EstimatedReturn and BorrowerRate.

From the boxplots, we can see that the people who are self-employed have a the highest range of estimated return, while people who are retired have the lowest estimated return. The estimated return increase with a better prosper rating.

From the boxplots, we can observe that self-employed people have the highest borrower rate followed by employed people and the retired people have the lowest borrower rate. The prosper rating increases with higher borrower rate.

From the chart above, we can see that employed people make the most people who take loans. Most of the employed people have a rating of C. They also have the most members with a ratong of AA followed by Full time and Self-employed. This would make sense because employed people have a consistent income, lenders are guranteed that the loans taken by employed people will be paid.
